reviews.text: Lovely place to visit. The crowd is always present. A beautiful sight to behold in the evening more so than during the day. Only reason I did not give it a 5 star rating is because the prices of the shops are a bit much as this is a tourist hot spot. Ensure you Bargain !!! . Lots of restaurants within the Stupa and just outside too. You cannot hang flags any longer on it since the earthquake.

It's picturesque historical and religious places with striking market containing fascinating Buddhism art, gallery as well as various sort of delicious cuisine.
Visit once time You will feel ecstatic.

Does exactly what it says on the tin... It's the biggest Stupa (Buddhist temple) in Kathmandu and is a lovely place to while away an hour or so watching the crowds come and go from one of the many rooftop bars that surround the location.

Be sure you navigate the stupa in a clockwise direction and you will encounter many monks and other visitors doing the same whilst spinning the many prayer wheels that line the perimeter.

You can climb up to the first level and take a while to sit and drink in the atmosphere... Be aware and respectful of the fact this is a religious site and you'll be just fine... Just don't mess about and, as the signs inform you, "no immoral behaviour".

Amazingly almost entirely undamaged by the earthquake in 2015 this is a must see for your visit to Kathmandu
Serene and peaceful. You get a very positive vibes and stress free moment. You won't regret 5 rounds of Boudhanath stupa.

Best religious place for Buddhist peoples. But everyone one can visit there and enjoy. This place is very calm and pleasing. Please do visit this place at evening time,you will get some better photos captured. #boudhastupa

One of the culturally significant place, it is a must go for tourists who are in Kathmandu. The place holds Hindu and Buddhist cultural values and is known for homing monkeys that you need to be wary of. It is best to visit the place at night as the entire city lights can be viewed.

Swayambhunath is an ancient religious architecture atop a hill in the Kathmandu Valley, west of Kathmandu city.This is one of the main attraction in Nepal. Its has an amazing view from the top and amazing art.You can enter from two sides. One is the long stairway, the other is not so tough if you're not up for a challenge. I was there at sunset and it was lovely . Also get a good view of the mountain range from here . Shopping is great and decent priced.
The Famous Buddhist Temple. Nice views of Kathmandu valley. Feel like the view from a 500m tall view tower.

Amazing place!
Very high....same like Baguio city in Philippines...
But if your already on top...it's wonderful!
You will see the very nice view from top.. Mo
Mind blowing, super cool, eternal peaceful, enlightened Buddhism holy place. Everyone from all over the world, must visit here once in life. One of the world heritage.

Worth a visit if you're visiting Kathmandu. A place of significant importance, it's one of the holiest places for Hindus worldwide. The Sadhus are open to having their photos taken for a some rupees. You might have the chance to observe an actual cremation. Be respectful and observe from a distance, especially if you take photos.

One of the most sacred Hindu temples of Nepal – Pashupatinath Temple is located on both banks of Bagmati River on the eastern outskirts of Kathmandu.

Pashupatinath is the most important temple dedicated to god Shiva. Every year this temple attracts hundreds of elderly followers of Hinduism.

They arrive here to find shelter for the last several weeks of their lives, to meet death, be cremated on the banks of the river and travel their last journey with the waters of the sacred river Bagmati, which later meets the holy river Ganges. Hinduists from every corner of Nepal and India are arriving here to die.

It is believed that those who die in Pashupatinath Temple are reborn as a human, regardless of any misconduct that could worsen their karma. The exact day of their death is predicted by astrologers of the temple. If you are attracted to the places where the spirit of death can be felt, then consider Pashupatinath as your first destination. It is a temple with special atmosphere of death; death is present in almost every ritual and every corner of it.

يقع أحد المعابد الهندوسية الأكثر قداسة في نيبال - معبد باشوباتيناث على ضفتي نهر باغماتي على المشارف الشرقية لكاتماندو.

Pashupatinath هو المعبد الأكثر أهمية مكرس للإله شيفا. يستقطب هذا المعبد كل عام مئات من كبار السن من أتباع الديانة الهندوسية.

يصلون إلى هنا لإيجاد مأوى خلال الأسابيع القليلة الماضية من حياتهم ، لمواجهة الموت ، وإحراق جثثهم على ضفاف النهر والسفر في رحلتهم الأخيرة مع مياه نهر باغماتي المقدس ، الذي يجتمع لاحقًا مع نهر الجانج المقدس. الهندوس من كل ركن من أركان نيبال والهند يصلون إلى هنا ليموتوا.

من المعتقد أن أولئك الذين يموتون في معبد باشوباتيناث يولدون من جديد كإنسان ، بغض النظر عن أي سوء سلوك قد يؤدي إلى تفاقم كارماهم. ويتوقع المنجمون في المعبد يوم موتهم بالضبط. إذا انجذبت إلى الأماكن التي يمكن أن تشعر بها روح الموت ، فاعتبر أن باشوباتيناث هي وجهتك الأولى. إنه هيكل ذو جو خاص من الموت. الموت موجود في كل طقوس تقريبًا وفي كل ركن من أركانها.

The Pashupatinath Temple (Nepali: पशुपतिनाथ मन्दिर) is a famous and sacred Hindu temple complex that is located on the banks of the Bagmati River, approximately 5 kilometres north-east of Kathmandu in the eastern part of Kathmandu Valley, the capital of Nepal. The temple serves as the seat of Nepal's national deity, Lord Pashupatinath. 
Lord Shiva is the one of the most popular gods of Hindu.

What to write about Shree Pashupatinath Temple. Divine place. Fortunate to be here in this lifetime. The most famous, oldest, highly regarded temple of the country. It is also the UNESCO world heritage site. Jay Shambho. Nepal Kathmandu

The most famous Hindu temple of in Kathmandu. It's very clean n rush is managed quite well. There are many other places near temple to see n enjoy. One river is also running behind the River where cremation is done.  Firstly  foreigners or other community people is not allowed or Hindus with leather belt or purse is not allowed.
It use to have amazing Nepali cultural heritage which has been destroyed by the earthquake. However, they have preserved most of the thing you would want to see. Also, it will soon be renovated ...
When i visited here restoration world was in progress so not much was for show but u can watch masterpiece of Nepalese architect.
In this place we see many things old times of King's thing. Old wood with beautiful art.
Probably the oldest collection of Nepal 🇳🇵 could be found here
All ancient collections you can see in a single place...

The buildings in which the family were killed are no longer standing, however you are able to walk near where they once stood. The main part of the palace has been immaculately preserved. An absolute time capsule! The palace has not been standing for centuries as it was only completed in the 60's,  which means it feels quite retro. 

No photography allowed inside and you cannot simply wonder around. The areas open to the public can be taken at self-pace however attendants will keep you moving along.

previously  used as a royal palace, narayanhiti is now a museum  opened to public. Narayanhiti has its own historical importance and  provides answer to curiosities of general people  about how and what a royal palace looks from inside. The place as a museum now contains many things , daily items and decorative items, used by the then kings of Nepal. After being dethroned , the king now lives in his own house as general people. Students can visit the place with low price tickets .

It has preserved the precious history of the kingship of Nepal. The gifts, artifacts, treasures, are its best features. It also reflects the culture and customs of the late king and queens. However, some places are still not accessible to general public. Hope it would be open and managed soon.

This is the palace where the monarchy used to reside until a decade ago from when on it has been turned into a museum. Unlike many museums, most of the artifacts here are fairly recent and in use till few decades ago. You walk through a number of rooms used by the erstwhile Kings and their guests. One of the best exhibits is the royal throne housed in the coronation chamber.
The museum closes at 4 PM sharp and they start moving out people by  3:15. If you plan to spend some time here observing everything suggest you reach in the first half of the day.

Narayanhiti Palace Museum is the former royal palace that is right at the centre of the capital of Nepal in Kathmandu. Narayanhiti Palace Museum the palace that for a very long time served as the chief residence for the nation’s sovereign rulers until Nepal ceased to be a monarchy in 2008. The Narayanhiti Palace Museum was turned into a museum then and was made open to the public. Now everyday Nepali citizens as well as people from all over the world can get the chance to look at the Narayanhiti Palace Museum.

Very small museum, cool knowledgeable guides that seem to master a lot of the countrie's historic, traditional and mythological stories. In an hour you can see most part of it. There is a little shop outside of the museum where you can buy some artifacts that are also available elsewhere at lesser price.
I like this place but I would love it if it had enough traditional and local object. I think it doesn't represent enough the national heritage

I loved visiting this museum. I wish I could've taken pictures. Nevertheless, our tour guide, William Dayo, was very well versed in each of the exhibits. It was really nice to have someone with us who gave us in depth information on what we were viewing. It gave us a deeper understanding and appreciation for each of the artifacts.
It was nice. The museum has a lot to offer in cultural history and I was happy to see them opened on a Sunday.

This museum continues the tradition of equating Western African culture and history mainly with masks (sarcasm). It could almost be interchangeable with the museum's in Dakar and Bamako except they both have a second floor dedicated to textiles. 

Granted, the masks are interesting and high quality, but they are completely decontextualized with cryptic captions an little explanation tying anything together.

There is one table showing the evolution of money that was nice. 

It's one of the few times I wished there was a museum gift shop with some books. 

Weirdly they don't allow photography either, as if history should be hidden. 

Avoid the restaurant out back it is way overpriced and there are better maquis around.

The Museum was Amazing. Price of admission LKR100 for Local. We spent around 5 hours there but if we read every text and looked at everything in detail we could've easily spent 1 day there.
Lovely Place, Interesting display of collection. Educating.Nice touch, very Clean and very friendly staff as well. Great for Students.   
I'd love to come back here.

I had read other reviews about this museum and thought the comments about the lack of air con were a bit precious, but they weren't. It was uncomfortably hot in there. The exhibitions make up for that however. There is a wealth of amazing artifacts for you to cruise. If you like museums then this is a must. As a bonus check out the street of people selling amazing paintings roadside at the back exit of the museum.

One of the best museums I've ever been to in my life. I was so impressed with the signage and the layout, the storytelling, the design. It was so delightful to also be able to see so much rich heritage without signs constantly reminding you about items stolen by the British (which are in the British Museum).

Museum with a lot of history from the dawn of time till modern days. More than 10 rooms containing history, artefacts and beauty. The building itself is gorgeous and the park is breathtaking. If you visit Colombo, this place is a MUST destination.

This is a great museum. The attached gem store is also government certified. The museum itself has a great short history of Sri Lanka in the first five rooms. Highlights include a kind of Rosetta stone, the fact that there was a canal system over most of the island several thousand years ago, and trinkets from various other civilizations due to Sri Lanka being on the sea silk route. About 2-3 hours needed. The colonial building it is in, is also nice. Go.

This is a special artsy place in Bulawayo City Centre. You must visit the artist studios where you get an intimate feel of the beautiful art work while it's been made. The store there also have wonderful paintings so it's a great place  to purchase gifts.

Very difficult rating for me. Food was great. Place not very clean. A little dusting, a fan, ready waiters and easy to move chairs to allow customers to sit well would greatly improve the place. So its a place with great potential just not being managed properly.
Artwork is superb and people vibe is good during exhibition nights on Wednesday .
Real good place. Home of the limitless
It's a nice Quiet place to look at beautiful paintings and more art work

The place is perfect for hosting exhibitions and has spacious rooms and architecture that allows experimentation for people displaying their art. The place holds a lot of exhibitions and you can follow their social media page to keep track of the exhibitions and programs.

Nepal Art Council is the biggest art gallery in Kathmandu located at Babarmahal, good transport facility to reach gallery  anywhere from  Kathmandu,gallery having two floor exhibitions hall have enough space for artists to showcase their works,management is very co operative and helping, however visitors are little less,spot light system should be need more advance,over all its a good gallery in Nepal,
A place to satisfy your artistic hunger,
Here,i ve seen many artistic painting.

Caught three exhibitions at once and it was good. Really liked photos from 'The Karnali: Photos from the Sacred River Corridor' by photographers Nabin Baral and Ramesh Bhusal. The attached photo is by Nabin Baral and one of my favorites.

A little bit of peace in the bustling intensity of Delhi. Simple garden to walk around (after you have been through airport style security and bag scans). Then, after taking off your shoes (you can leave them for free or pay a small fee for them to be looked after), you can go into the smaller central area to see the black marble platform marking the spot where Gandhi’s was cremated and the eternal flame...the garden has a number of Gandhi’s quotes dotted around it....

This was one of the highlights of my visit to Delhi and I left this place deeply contented. I would suggest coming here in the mornings and evenings before the sun scorches the paths. Thought inspiring quotes line the magnificent memorial to one of our greatest leaders. The site is kept meticulously clean and beautiful flowers lighten the atmosphere. I would suggest removing your socks before walking on the wet grass path to avoid wet and uncomfortable socks.

Beautiful lavish green surrounding makes the visit to  this memorial a pleasant and memorable one. Rightly being maintained for the father of the nation, it's quite a treat to soothe your soul amidst the Flora and fauna. The parking is well maintained with a cafeteria and well maintained restrooms. 
Please don't forget to leave behind all the eatables, including toffees and chocolate. Nothing is permitted inside.

It is a beautiful place. There are very good quotes by Mahatma Gandhi written along the sides.
Its more suited to visit this place with family or if you are serious about the importance of this place.
 One good thing from this is that we did not have to walk around on the soil and turf without our shoes on. The site is very large and very respectful to a great man. The eternal flame pays due homage.

Raj Ghat

It was a memorial place for Gandhi.

It pretty much were just a park with flowers and things.

When I reached there it was closed to be cleaned for someone important who wanted to come the next day.

It was beautiful but not that special.

Near it there were some good restaurants to go eat something .

Great store to buy daily use items. Good price and the owner is very friendly. You would hardly find any place to buy your day to day items which is better than that. If you come here regularly you would feel like almost family. I love this place, i never buy anything from other shops unless it becomes out if stock from this place. This is the most famous shop also...
Love this
Excellent service and very friendly people out there.

Delicious food and reasonably priced! The service was very friendly and even helped finding fun locations to visit. Food was served with great portions quickly with a smile. Highly recommended for all type of consumers including vegan, vegetarian and meat eaters alike. Healthy options available.

I thought the food was very fresh and the fried rice was very refreshing it was a cute little treasure over the bridge. what is it the chicken puffs we're a little greasy but they were delicious. Very clean clean place to eat.

Decided to order some Thai food today for my birthday, I’ve heard nothing but good things about TukTuk so far.I ordered the crab Rangoon‘s and a chicken stirfry. I also decided to get a Thai iced tea as well. Everything from top to bottom was absolutely amazing the tea was perfectly sweet and delicious, and my favorite crab Rangoon‘s today. The chicken stirfry was cooked perfectly  with a beautiful blend of flavors. I would highly recommend 5out of 5 stars.
WOW!!!! Extremely flavorful- seriously the best Thai that I’ve ever EVER had! Also the delivery guy was super nice 😊

The food was pretty average and definitely not the best I've had. I thought it was overpriced, too. Especially for the amount of food. Maybe I'll try it again some time in the distant future to see if they improve but at the moment I don't really recommend trying.

Couple days ago while I was going through Mandala Street, and I saw some foreigners eating their steaks at New Orleans,. I thought they were having a good time enjoying their food. So I thought of going there someday.
      And that day was Friday 22nd March 2019 @5 pm. Today New Orleans was the lucky restaurant to get my hard earned money. Me and my sis. We took our seats, my sis ordered a vanilla milkshake and we both ordered our steak sizzler.
   The vanilla milkshake came and my sis tried it, she said that some was wrong with the shake. So I took a sip and damn that was a watered down shake, not a milk shake, no hint of vanilla. WTF, I wondered that a famous restaurant as this with its chefs, cooks and bartender would at least know how to not f up a shake. I told my sis I hope they don't f up my steak.
 There was some background music of kids crying and making noise. The steak sizzler came, it was plenty of food. So I chomped on it, there was no noodles in the sizzler. That's the first time and was served with this pita bread I guess. The gravy had a little more sodium than usual, but hey when u go to an expensive restaurant where u pay tax and vat, I make sure I eat all my money's worth. I guess it just wasn't my day.
    After we finished, we didn't want to take no more expensive risks so we went to pay. My sis asked the cashier, our waiter 'don't u serve sizzlers with noodles' .  He replied digging his ears which he served us with and said, ' We serve it with potatoes.' I was dumbfounded, does he even know what kind of food is served there or does he only know dalbhat.
  I took a leak and left the place. Wow, I had imagined the place with so high expectations but that's what I get when we expect too much, lesson for the day. Maybe 1 day I'll have some more extra money to burn, and I'll go there and order a cold beer. Now I know that they cannot  f up that.                    Thank you New Orleans goodbye

I am a carnivore. I love meat. To me there's nothing better than a juicy marinated piece of meat gently sizzling away over an open flame but to satisfy the varying dietary requirements of our group this place was chosen.

As much as I love meat, I did not miss it for this meal. All the food was vegetarian and it didn't bother me one bit. Every bite was a delight.

To meat lovers and vegetarians alike I highly recommend this restaurant. Great for sharing.
Awesome chill vibe, delicious food. Good music, cocktails and service too. Super clean, been to the Kathmandu and Pokhara ones several times now. Really delicious Mediterranean food

Large serves, fresh and tasty and cool vibe. Worth a post-trek checkout. Though it’s not quite 4.5 stars worth.
It was a true example for an authentic street food shop. It's has all the aspects of taste, cleaneniness and good service. Prices are reasonable, definitely worth it experience. ✌️

One of the best street food joints in Colombo. Ordered their Egg kotthu with creamy cheese. Generous portions and taste was really good. Not spicy at all. ( note that they have more spicy kotthu in their Menu) Worth for the price tag.

Staff is very friendly too. Devilled chicken koththu is very good while others too were better than many popular koththu places around. Highly recommended.

I highly suggest starting with their house made chips and guacamole. Service was great. Location was a bit tricky to find but once you see it, you’ll remember it. Definitely worth coming back to!

One of the best Mexican cuisine restaurants in Kathmandu... The only problem if you are a vegetarian like me is that most of the dishes they make for us have kidney beans or its sauce. So any item you order tends to get repetitive. Rest all is perfect barring this!

I have been stopping by since past 3 years. Though the owner has changed the food still tastes the same. If you love spice and Mexican food do stop by. This is the place you should not skip. Try it. They have gumballs too. 😊
